			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=469')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=43300&amp;TOPIC_ID=5358&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=Items+after+INT+is+maxed+out%3F&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         Try an experiment for yourself. If your INT is nearing 255, you should have lots of slots that are specificallly dedicated to INT. Borrow/buy some HP gear, enough to drop your INT to the 200ish mark, while beefing your HP up say 250-350 or so. Carry your INT items with you in a backpack.</P><P>When you are grouping swap a few times, see what INT gear does for you, and then see what HP gear does for you.</P><P>I guarantee you will soon see that for necros, your total HP makes a much greater contribution to your effectiveness then your total mana does. You will die less, be able to stay in lich/demi/arch longer, heal better, life tap DOT more efficiently, be in less situations where you gain agro from having low HP, ect, ect, ect. </P><P>There really is very little comparison. I truly believe that the only necros who rate mana pool over HP pool are also the ones that ask for Clarity during a raid.</P><P>Cheers,<BR>Ancagalon the Black<BR>Warlock - Terris Thule</P><P></P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

